00:35:02.620 --> 00:35:03.860
&gt;&gt;Dan Yates: Why do utilities do this?

00:35:03.860 --> 00:35:06.470
&gt;&gt;Female #2: Yeah, what's the model there?

00:35:06.470 --> 00:35:09.280
&gt;&gt;Dan Yates: Mmhmm.

00:35:09.280 --> 00:35:11.150
Great question.

00:35:11.150 --> 00:35:14.310
[pause] There's a couple different answers.

00:35:14.310 --> 00:35:20.900
The way we started the business was very focused
on energy efficiency.

00:35:20.900 --> 00:35:27.410
Utilities have state mandates that require
them to hit these efficiency standards that

00:35:27.410 --> 00:35:30.320
are called energy efficiency resource standards.

00:35:30.320 --> 00:35:35.410
Basically every populous state in the US now
has a standard that these utilities are being

00:35:35.410 --> 00:35:36.520
held to.

00:35:36.520 --> 00:35:42.650
What happens is the utility commission in
each state will set a goal, a certain terawatt

00:35:42.650 --> 00:35:47.340
hour goal or gigawatt hour goal that we've
passed down pro rata to the utilities in that

00:35:47.340 --> 00:35:48.340
state.

00:35:48.340 --> 00:35:53.850
The utilities will then put together a portfolio
of programs that are proposed back to the

00:35:53.850 --> 00:35:55.290
commission every 3 years.

00:35:55.290 --> 00:36:01.420
Based upon the costs of those programs, they
will put a tax on the utility bill that funds

00:36:01.420 --> 00:36:03.930
these programs.

00:36:03.930 --> 00:36:08.200
That's been-- And from a utility perspective
in this regard, it's really compliance exercise.

00:36:08.200 --> 00:36:11.300
They don't have any stake in it, but they've
been mandated to do it.

00:36:11.300 --> 00:36:16.870
And they definitely adhere to commission mandates
because they commission is their one customer,

00:36:16.870 --> 00:36:20.940
really, where they get approval or denial
for building new things.

00:36:20.940 --> 00:36:25.940
That was the core value proposition for us
starting the company.

00:36:25.940 --> 00:36:27.890
What's happened now is we've grown.

00:36:27.890 --> 00:36:32.350
As the utility industry has started to evolve
in this direction, as utilities are realizing

00:36:32.350 --> 00:36:38.550
that their future is much more consumer centric
than it ever has been, or certainly for the

00:36:38.550 --> 00:36:40.270
last 85 years.

00:36:40.270 --> 00:36:43.590
Many of them may be, more than they wish it
were.

00:36:43.590 --> 00:36:47.970
But as this political spotlight has been shined
on the utility industry, it's not easy to

00:36:47.970 --> 00:36:50.430
go build a dirty coal plant anymore.

00:36:50.430 --> 00:36:58.050
So to hit capacity requirements, to handle
new population growth, and to invest in new

00:36:58.050 --> 00:37:01.490
infrastructure, which is how utilities make
money, they're finding that all of their new

00:37:01.490 --> 00:37:05.160
investments inevitably are more consumer intertwined.

00:37:05.160 --> 00:37:08.270
Whether it's smart meters where we've all
heard about the crazy ruckus here about people

00:37:08.270 --> 00:37:13.142
being upset about them, or peak reduction
programs where they try to get you to install

00:37:13.142 --> 00:37:16.290
a thermostat that reduces your peak usage.

00:37:16.290 --> 00:37:19.530
There's a lot of interaction you have to have
with the consumer.

00:37:19.530 --> 00:37:23.840
So as utilities are moving in that direction,
they're realizing they need this consumer

00:37:23.840 --> 00:37:29.940
infrastructure to engage customers and to
be able to provide a better value.

00:37:29.940 --> 00:37:33.680
Also, as rates are rising, which is the other
thing that's happening, is people are not

00:37:33.680 --> 00:37:35.600
allowing coal plants to be built.

00:37:35.600 --> 00:37:39.840
So for all these reasons, it becomes politically
very important for the utility to have a much

00:37:39.840 --> 00:37:42.170
better capability to engage the consumer.

00:37:42.170 --> 00:37:45.530
That's how, as we've grown, how this has grown.

00:37:45.530 --> 00:37:49.900
It's still the core-- What we like to say
is an energy efficient customer is a happy

00:37:49.900 --> 00:37:54.020
customer 'cause we just want to save money
on our bills.

00:37:54.020 --> 00:37:55.990
That's a major factor.

00:37:55.990 --> 00:37:59.810
So the question is, we have this feedback
loop where we're sending signals once a month.

00:37:59.810 --> 00:38:02.620
Do we have the capability to send it faster.

00:38:02.620 --> 00:38:04.500
We definitely have the capability to send
it faster.

00:38:04.500 --> 00:38:09.700
Then the question is-- We're taking 6 minutes
a year of attention up to 12 minutes.

00:38:09.700 --> 00:38:12.430
Can we take it up to 400 minutes?

00:38:12.430 --> 00:38:16.220
I think at some point, the answer is no, people
don't actually want to think about their energy

00:38:16.220 --> 00:38:17.230
use that much.

00:38:17.230 --> 00:38:24.030
So where we're focused-- One of our mantras
for a long time has been insights in analytics

00:38:24.030 --> 00:38:25.460
trump real time.

00:38:25.460 --> 00:38:28.350
People actually don't want to get feedback
constantly.

00:38:28.350 --> 00:38:34.770
They want to get more and more, richer and
richer, more and more tailored feedback.

00:38:34.770 --> 00:38:37.810
I always come back to-- I was thinking about
what would my mom want to get?

00:38:37.810 --> 00:38:43.420
My mom would love to get a notice in the spring
that says, "Last summer was a doozy.

00:38:43.420 --> 00:38:46.400
You paid twice as much as your neighbors on
AC.

00:38:46.400 --> 00:38:52.490
Here's the top three things you should do
to save energy this summer on air conditioning."

00:38:52.490 --> 00:38:57.520
Rather than getting a weekly or daily email
about her energy use.

00:38:57.520 --> 00:39:04.680
That being said, one of the features we've
just rolled out is a weekly smart meter-enabled

00:39:04.680 --> 00:39:08.400
update on your usage for people who are engaged
at that level.

00:39:08.400 --> 00:39:10.220
We do emails as frequently as people want.

00:39:10.220 --> 00:39:12.010
We do alerts now.

00:39:12.010 --> 00:39:18.900
We're doing, for some of these utilities that
have load reduction days, we'll send out,

00:39:18.900 --> 00:39:25.710
for one utility, 2 million emails in 30 minutes
because we've got to get all of these people

00:39:25.710 --> 00:39:27.880
this information.

00:39:27.880 --> 00:39:31.970
So I'm hearing two different questions.

00:39:31.970 --> 00:39:34.140
Let's see if I can answer this.

00:39:34.140 --> 00:39:40.930
[pause] There's this long term challenge of,
okay, so if everybody installs the residential

00:39:40.930 --> 00:39:44.300
PV, there's no-- efficiency doesn't matter
anymore.

00:39:44.300 --> 00:39:48.810
I've two thoughts, I've number of thoughts
on that.

00:39:48.810 --> 00:39:50.320
One is, God, that'd be awesome.

00:39:50.320 --> 00:39:55.670
I'd be happy to go out of business if everybody
loaded up with a solar PV.

00:39:55.670 --> 00:39:59.220
But on top of that, that's going to be a long,
slow slog.

00:39:59.220 --> 00:40:02.950
We've been at it for, it's really in earnest
been going on for 5 years now.

00:40:02.950 --> 00:40:09.600
I think that they're just nearing 100,000
solar homes in the US, which is 1/1000 of

00:40:09.600 --> 00:40:10.990
the number of homes.

00:40:10.990 --> 00:40:13.170
So we've got a long way to go.

00:40:13.170 --> 00:40:18.510
Within that, I think there's a ton of opportunity
for us to help promote solar, to help report

00:40:18.510 --> 00:40:23.910
back on solar, to aggregate solar on lots
of different things that can be done, and

00:40:23.910 --> 00:40:28.310
to be involved in selling it, not just promoting
it.

00:40:28.310 --> 00:40:30.370
And financing, etcetera.

00:40:30.370 --> 00:40:36.740
That, to me, is a long term opportunity and
problem, and in the same timeframe as solar

00:40:36.740 --> 00:40:41.200
starts to happen, that's why we are getting
into the things like thermostats.

00:40:41.200 --> 00:40:46.021
And we'll be-- As electric vehicles become
more scaled, we'll be looking at what we can

00:40:46.021 --> 00:40:48.900
do there.

00:40:48.900 --> 00:40:53.090
The other question was about what if behavior
dries up.

00:40:53.090 --> 00:40:59.790
That one is-- I've got at least 100,000 years
of evolutionary history to say that we're

00:40:59.790 --> 00:41:02.440
going to stick with the pack for the next
100 years.

00:41:02.440 --> 00:41:04.410
That one I'm not too worried about.

