For example, with social, when we turned it

00:46:02.460 --> 00:46:06.120
on for a new utility, we didn't have to get
any more data from them.

00:46:06.120 --> 00:46:07.170
We already had it.

00:46:07.170 --> 00:46:14.330
But we are only monetizing probably 10% of
that data that we have under management.

00:46:14.330 --> 00:46:21.550
So a good example is when we sold Com Edison
in the Illinois region and Chicago land area.

00:46:21.550 --> 00:46:26.020
We had a 50,000 home program with them, and
they gave us all 3 million homes worth of

00:46:26.020 --> 00:46:28.350
data.

00:46:28.350 --> 00:46:32.200
That's the case all over the place.

00:46:32.200 --> 00:46:36.800
To talk about our business, our TAM is in
the multiple billions of dollars, between

00:46:36.800 --> 00:46:40.730
3 and 5 billion.

00:46:40.730 --> 00:46:44.360
We're nowhere near that right now in terms
of our growth.

00:46:44.360 --> 00:46:50.950
As we serve-- There's a lot of great stuff
ahead of us.

00:46:50.950 --> 00:46:55.380
so our big expansion areas are domestically
in the US we still have new utilities to sell,

00:46:55.380 --> 00:46:58.080
and we have a lot of expansion with our existing
utilities.

00:46:58.080 --> 00:47:02.370
And then we're just now starting to really
expand internationally.

00:47:02.370 --> 00:47:04.710
That opportunity is as big as the US opportunity.

00:47:04.710 --> 00:47:07.000
And that's just market expansion.

00:47:07.000 --> 00:47:12.170
Then we continue to build new products, like
this thermostat which I'm excited about.

00:47:12.170 --> 00:47:16.180
It's going to be a total new product line.

00:47:16.180 --> 00:47:17.180
It's actually interesting.

00:47:17.180 --> 00:47:20.340
We haven't actually looked that much at the
interfaces much on cars . We did-- I was at

00:47:20.340 --> 00:47:27.150
an event last spring, and I actually talked
to a business development guy from GM who

00:47:27.150 --> 00:47:30.390
said, "Hey, you should come talk to us, 'cause
we're designing some new cars and we want

00:47:30.390 --> 00:47:31.780
to talk to you about the interface."

00:47:31.780 --> 00:47:35.140
And we just didn't make it high enough up
on the priority list.

00:47:35.140 --> 00:47:38.050
We didn't feel like it was believable.

00:47:38.050 --> 00:47:42.400
It's going to be small scale, and they don't
have an electric car yet, or they almost do

00:47:42.400 --> 00:47:45.800
but not quite.

00:47:45.800 --> 00:47:47.200
So that is an interesting opportunity.

00:47:47.200 --> 00:47:49.530
I think we haven't looked into that that much.

00:47:49.530 --> 00:47:56.250
The area where we've thought a little bit
more is charging management, because that's

00:47:56.250 --> 00:48:01.040
where the utilities-- The utilities are thrilled
that there's going to be these new power consumers

00:48:01.040 --> 00:48:04.120
on their grid using up more energy, and they
can make money off of them.

00:48:04.120 --> 00:48:07.680
But what they're confused about is: how's
this going to work?

00:48:07.680 --> 00:48:13.430
Because an electric vehicle in charging mode
is like a house, so it's like you're driving

00:48:13.430 --> 00:48:15.690
houses around and jamming them into the grid.

00:48:15.690 --> 00:48:17.520
All of a sudden, the transformer melts.

00:48:17.520 --> 00:48:23.060
That's very, very expensive compared to the
value of the electricity from the car.

00:48:23.060 --> 00:48:27.850
So they're trying to get a handle on how they
manage that.

00:48:27.850 --> 00:48:33.710
There are lots of companies that are astutely
going after this in a way that we haven't

00:48:33.710 --> 00:48:36.900
yet, but it's an area that we're monitoring.

00:48:36.900 --> 00:48:38.460
&gt;&gt; Male #6: Inaudible

00:48:38.460 --> 00:48:44.100
&gt;&gt;Yeah, so there's a lot of different-- people
taking a lot of different tacks.

00:48:44.100 --> 00:48:48.540
One is the charging station that works like
Zipcar for charging.

00:48:48.540 --> 00:48:49.910
Well, not really, but whatever.

00:48:49.910 --> 00:48:50.910
You get it.

00:48:50.910 --> 00:48:55.280
And another way is, Better Place has tried
to do it, where you have replaceable batteries

00:48:55.280 --> 00:49:00.230
and there's essentially gas stations for batteries.

00:49:00.230 --> 00:49:04.130
And then there's the third way, which is that
people just don't have either and you just

00:49:04.130 --> 00:49:11.450
charge your car at home and maybe cut a deal
at your office to charge your car there.

00:49:11.450 --> 00:49:19.010
I think it's to be seen how much these other--
I think this is all early days.

00:49:19.010 --> 00:49:21.100
It's to be seen what's going to stick or not.

00:49:21.100 --> 00:49:22.930
&gt;&gt;Male #7: Is it that bad?

00:49:22.930 --> 00:49:26.340
&gt;&gt;No, I think it's actually not that complicated.

00:49:26.340 --> 00:49:33.100
There are a lot of decoy facts out there that
are hard to parse out, like the tiered pricing,

00:49:33.100 --> 00:49:38.380
which is a mandated structure from-- This
is a California phenomenon.

00:49:38.380 --> 00:49:44.920
It's manned by the utility commission as a
way to try to, essentially, charge rich people

00:49:44.920 --> 00:49:48.770
more for electricity and discourage overconsumption.

00:49:48.770 --> 00:49:52.650
But that's not a fact of the energy market.

00:49:52.650 --> 00:49:55.560
It's a policy manipulation.

00:49:55.560 --> 00:50:01.890
The core dynamic is-- Just think about cell
phone companies.

00:50:01.890 --> 00:50:04.100
They have a network they put a lot of money
into.

00:50:04.100 --> 00:50:06.180
They want you to use it.

00:50:06.180 --> 00:50:13.240
But they max out at peak times, and then they
have these trough times where there's no usage.

00:50:13.240 --> 00:50:20.050
Just like cell phone networks, they have all
these-- they can't shut down the base stations

00:50:20.050 --> 00:50:21.460
at night.

00:50:21.460 --> 00:50:26.610
Even if they did, it doesn't matter because
the base station is you build as many of them

00:50:26.610 --> 00:50:30.910
out to meet peak demand, not because of--
and so it's just wasted at night.

00:50:30.910 --> 00:50:35.170
The cell phone companies would be happy to
pay you, probably, to use their network.

00:50:35.170 --> 00:50:36.570
It means nothing to them at night time.

00:50:36.570 --> 00:50:39.300
It's why they have nights and weekend plans.

00:50:39.300 --> 00:50:47.580
So it's the exact same thing with utilities
and with the peak usage and the off-time usage.

00:50:47.580 --> 00:50:53.850
And with coal plants, the problem is, and
with all these baseload plants, is they literally

00:50:53.850 --> 00:50:58.490
take 24 hours to power up, so they can't shut
them off at night.

00:50:58.490 --> 00:51:03.360
So that is not just a waste of capital in
the infrastructure, but it's actually a huge

00:51:03.360 --> 00:51:06.720
waste of emissions and fuel.

00:51:06.720 --> 00:51:09.400
So the utilities are motivated to reduce peak.

00:51:09.400 --> 00:51:11.990
They have an endemic interest in doing that.

00:51:11.990 --> 00:51:19.090
Then the commissions, which are-- you should
think of them as your proxy-- are motivated

00:51:19.090 --> 00:51:23.320
in reducing overall usage because they want
to save people money and help the environment.

00:51:23.320 --> 00:51:27.890
So the commissions will set these efficiency
standards, and the utilities go out and try

00:51:27.890 --> 00:51:30.440
to come up with ways to shave peak.

00:51:30.440 --> 00:51:35.730
Those are basically the two major dynamics.

00:51:35.730 --> 00:51:37.910
In the top hours, it's a loss.

00:51:37.910 --> 00:51:41.290
In the worst hours of the year, it can be
a loss, depending on the utility.

00:51:41.290 --> 00:51:46.080
If the utility has their own generation or
they're buying on the open market.

00:51:46.080 --> 00:51:47.080
Yeah.

00:51:47.080 --> 00:51:55.130
When the utility exec wakes up in the morning,
he does not want, or she does not want, to

00:51:55.130 --> 00:51:57.130
deliver energy efficiency.

00:51:57.130 --> 00:51:58.180
They may be interested.

00:51:58.180 --> 00:52:01.410
They are in many cases interested in reducing
peak.

00:52:01.410 --> 00:52:05.830
And then the commission wakes up in the morning
and says, "I want to save citizens of California

00:52:05.830 --> 00:52:07.870
energy and money and help the environment."

00:52:07.870 --> 00:52:12.920
And that's the group who says, "Let's have
an efficiency standard."

00:52:12.920 --> 00:52:17.090
And then the utility says, "Well, if they
want it, I got to endear myself to them because

00:52:17.090 --> 00:52:19.960
they're my buyer, when I go to try to sell
this next thing.

00:52:19.960 --> 00:52:23.300
So maybe I should take into consideration
this efficiency stuff."

00:52:23.300 --> 00:52:29.920
And then the complex political intertanglings
continue to unfold.

00:52:29.920 --> 00:52:32.310
But those are the two major fundamentals.

00:52:32.310 --> 00:52:34.280
All right.

00:52:34.280 --> 00:52:36.080
Thank you guys so much for so many great questions.

00:52:36.080 --> 00:52:36.290
[applause]

